"'''Mercy'''" is a single from the album ''[[Rockferry (album)|Rockferry]]'' by [[Duffy (singer)|Duffy]]. Co-written and produced by Steve Booker. The song which has received a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]]<ref>[http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/12/03/lil-wayne-coldplay-lead-nominations-for-51st-annual-grammy-awards/ Lil Wayne, Coldplay Lead Nominations for 51st Annual Grammy Awards Rolling Stone 3 December, 2008]</ref> was made available for download in the UK from [[February 11]], [[2008]] and was released physically on [[February 25]], [[2008]].

On [[February 17]], the song entered the [[UK Singles Chart]] at number one solely on download sales and remained at the top of the charts for five weeks. The retro-soul style is given further significance by the appearance of several [[Northern Soul]] dancers in the song's video. As of 25 July 2008, Mercy has been viewed on [[YouTube]] over 25 million times.<ref>[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KE2orthS3TQ]</ref> Mercy is included in the [[FIFA 09]] soundtrack.<ref>[http://www.fifa09.ea.com/us/readnews/entryid/25050]</ref> 

Mercy was the best selling single of 2008 in the UK with over 420,000 sales until the end of the year when it was overtaken by [[Hero]] by the [[List of The X Factor finalists (UK series 5)|X Factor Finalists]] and [[Hallelujah]] by X Factor winner [[Alexandra Burke]]. Mercy was the third best selling single of 2008 in the UK with over 500,000 sales.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_7800000/newsid_7803400/7803437.stm</ref> Elsewhere, it managed to chart within many countries top ten end of year bestseller lists. Interestingly, in [[Australia]], despite only attaining a peak of 26, it was the 72nd biggest selling song there in 2008. This included a Gold certification, certifying 35,000 sales in Australia.

== Song information ==
According to Duffy, the song is autobiographical and is about "sexual liberty" and "not doing something somebody else wants you to do".<ref>[http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2008/03/26/new-video-duffy-mercy/ MTV Buzzworthy blog]</ref> In an interview the singer also likened singing Mercy to having sex and said she loved to sing it as she felt it was like "having sex everyday".<ref>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4wnS5YM3of4</ref>  

The introduction of the song is somewhat reminiscent of the opening bars of '[[Stand by Me (song)|Stand by Me]]' by Ben E King, although the intro to 'Stand By Me' uses 1 5 and major 7, while the intro to 'Mercy' uses 1 5 and b7, making it sound more "bluesey".  'Mercy' is written in the key of G major and the chord progression used is the 12 bar blues so the main chords are I,IV,V.

"Mercy" won the [[2008 MOJO Awards|2008]] [[MOJO Awards|MOJO Award]] for Song of the Year. The award is voted by readers of the magazine. The magazines editor Phil Alexander called the song a "timeless" classic that " could really have come from any period in time over the last 50 years".<ref name="telegraph.co.uk">[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/2139775/Duffy-wins-big-with-Mercy-at-Mojo-Awards.html Duffy wins big with Mercy at Mojo Awards The Telegraph 16 June, 2008]</ref> The song was used as Duffy's debut single internationally.

[[The Game (rapper)|The Game]] has remixed this song, as has Gareth Wyn.

===Promotion and Cultural Use===
[[Duffy (singer)|Duffy]] also performed this song at the [[MTV|MTV European Music Awards]] where 'Mercy' was nominated for 'Most Addictive Track' and Duffy being nominated for 'Best New Act'. She also performed the track along with new single, "[[Rain On Your Parade]]", on the [[BBC]] [[Children in Need]] charity appeal.

In September 2008, Duffy performed this song on [[Saturday Night Live]], along with [[Stepping Stone (Duffy song)|Stepping Stone]]. The song is on the soundtrack for ''[[Sex and the City: The Movie]]''.<ref>[http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/album_reviews/s/1051314_sex_and_the_city__original_motion_picture_soundtrack_decca_records_ Album Review for Sex and The City soundtrack Manchester Evening News 27 May, 2007]</ref>, and it appeared on the premiere for season 5 of the HBO show ''Entourage'' <U+201C>Mercy<U+201D> was used on the [[Xbox 360]] [[karaoke]] game [[Lips (video game)|Lips]].<ref>[http://blogs.theage.com.au/screenplay/archives/010549.html Get your Lips around this The Age 17 September, 2008]</ref> The song also features on the soundtrack to [[FIFA 09]].<ref>[http://musicunderfire.com/2008/09/fifa-2009-soundtrack-unveiled.html Music Under Fire: FIFA 2009 soundtrack unveiled]</ref> "Mercy" was used in the [[HBO]] series [[Entourage (TV series)]] Season 5 Episode 1.  An abbreviated version of the song was used as the opening theme for the US version of [[The Chopping Block]], which began airing on March 11, 2009.

==Critical Reception==
The track was received positively received by critics, with many noting the 'retro' feel of the song.  Editor of [[Mojo]] magazine, Phil Alexander, called the song a "timeless classic" that " could really have come from any period in time over the last 50 years".<ref name="telegraph.co.uk"/>. Digital Spy gave the single a very positive review, stating that the song was "a catchy, danceable Northern soul pastiche" and that the "bassline practically reeks of sweat and stale cigarette smoke".

